==Latin==
{{wikipedia|lang=la}}
===Etymology===
Borrowed from {{bor|la|grc|Œß|t=chi}}, which represented /ks/ in the dialects of most of the Greek mainland and Euboea.
===Pronunciation===
The sound of X was like that of the Greek {{m|el|Œû|t=xi}}, that is /ks/, although etymologically it represented not only ''cs'' (as in {{l|la|l≈´x}}, from luc-s, and {{l|la|dƒ´xƒ´}}, from dic-si), but also ''gs'' (as in {{l|la|lƒìx}}, from leg-s; {{l|la|rƒìxƒ´}}, from reg-si); ''hs'' (as in {{l|la|trƒÅxƒ´}}, from trah-si; {{l|la|vexƒ´}}, from veh-si); and ''chs'' (as in the word {{l|la|onyx}}, from onych-s, borrowed from the Greek). The
hardening of a softer final (''g'', ''h'', ''ch'') before ''s'' into the ''—Å'' sound, which occurs in the last-mentioned cases, is found also in several roots ending in ''v'' and ''u'': {{l|la|nix}} for niv-s, {{l|la|vƒ´xƒ´}} for viv-si, {{l|la|connixƒ´}} for conniv-si, {{l|la|fluxƒ´}} for fluv-si, from {{l|la|flu≈ç}} (root fluv; cf. {{l|la|fluvius}}), {{l|la|struxƒ´}} for stru-si. Less frequently ''x'' has arisen from the combinations ''ps'' and ''ts'': {{l|la|proximus}} for prop-simus (from {{l|la|prope}}), {{l|la|nƒ´xus}} for nit-sus (from {{l|la|nƒ´tor}}), the latter being used along with the collateral form {{l|la|nƒ´sus}}, as also {{l|la|connƒ´vƒ´}} with {{l|la|connixƒ´}}, and {{l|la|mistus}} (from {{l|la|misce≈ç}}) with {{l|la|mixtus}}. An
exchange of the sounds ''ss'' or ''s'' and ''x'', took place in {{l|la|axis}} for assis and {{l|la|laxus}} for lassus. In the later language of the vulgar, the guttural sound in ''x'' disappeared, and ''s'' or ''ss'' was often written for it; as vis for {{l|la|vix}}, visit for {{l|la|vƒ´xit}}, unsit for {{l|la|unxit}}, conflississet for {{l|la|conflixisset}}, in late inscriptions; hence regularly in Italian, and frequently in the other Romance tongues, the Latin ''x'' is represented by ''s'' or ''ss''.
By a mere graphic variation, one of the constituent sounds of ''x'' is often expressed in inscriptions (but not the earliest) by an additional ''—Å'' or ''s''; as SACXO or SAXSO for {{l|la|sax≈ç}}; VCXOR or VXSOR for {{l|la|uxor}}; CONIVNCX or CONIVNXS for {{l|la|conjunx}}; even both sounds are sometimes thus expressed, VICXSIT for {{l|la|vƒ´xit}}.
